{
  "answer": "In Bṛhaspati Smṛti (work slug: unknown-brhaspati-smrti-0fd070, chapter 1), lekhya ('document' / writing as evidence) is one of three forms of human proof alongside witnesses (sākṣī) and possession/inference. Bṛhaspati devotes a distinct section (1.6, 'The Document') to it.\n\n**What lekhya is:** A lekhya is a written legal instrument that records a transaction. According to Brh_1,6.2, the Creator instituted writing precisely because 'confusion arises over time in matters of debt and the like' — lekhya is thus the instrument of temporal memory. A valid document must state the custom of the country, the year, month, fortnight, the interest, and bear the signature of the debtor, the witnesses, and the scribe (Brh_1,6.3). Bṛhaspati enumerates eight worldly document-types: partition deed, boundary deed, deed of gift, deed of sale, mortgage deed, bond of servitude, compact, and loan document — plus special royal documents (charter of gift, document of favor) and the judicial document of victory (Brh_1,6.4–8).\n\n**How it differs from sakshya (testimony):** The most important difference is hierarchical priority and durability.\n\n1. *Priority*: 'When a document exists in disputes, there should be neither an ordeal nor witnesses' (Brh_1,4.12). A document, when present and valid, displaces witness testimony entirely. Witness testimony (sakshya) is only called upon when no document exists or when doubt arises about a document.\n\n2. *Durability*: 'A document that is shown from time to time, read out, and reminded of, succeeds everywhere, even when the witnesses are dead' (Brh_1,6.45). Sakshya depends on living, morally qualified persons; lekhya outlasts them.\n\n3. *Nature of the evidence*: Sakshya is oral and personal — witnesses must be free from disqualifying traits (gamblers, violent men, those related to a party, etc.), must testify in exact conformity with the plaint, and are subject to impeachment. Lekhya is a material artifact; its validity is assessed by the physical document itself (letters, condition, signatures) rather than by the moral character of a person.\n\n4. *Limits of lekhya*: A document unused and unshown for thirty years loses validity even if its witnesses are still alive (Brh_1,6.47). Documents can be forged, and a flawed document (one made under duress, by a dying person, or with impeachable signatories) is invalidated (Brh_1,6.30–36). When doubt arises about a document, the statements of the debtor, witnesses, and scribe are used to clarify it (Brh_1,6.43) — so sakshya can serve as secondary corroboration for lekhya.\n\nIn sum: lekhya in Bṛhaspati is written proof that carries the highest evidentiary weight among human proofs, surpasses sakshya in priority when it exists, and is superior in preserving evidence across time; but it has its own formal requirements and vulnerability to forgery or disuse.",
